methods and under the assumption that a given system was monitored passively. Campbell and Nikoukhah's book proposes an "active" multimodel approach. It calls for applying an auxiliary signal that will affect the output so that it can be used to easily determine if there has been a failure and what type of failure it is. This auxiliary signal must be kept small, and often brief in duration, in order not to interfere with system performance and to ensure timely detection of the failure. The approach is robust and uses tools from robust control theory. Unlike some approaches, it is applicable to complex systems. The authors present the theory in a rigorous and intuitive manner and provide practical algorithms for implementation of the procedures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aFault location (Engineering). 0aSignal processing. 0aSystem failures (Engineering). 7aMATHEMATICS / Applied.2bisacsh  aA priori estimate.  aAIXI.  aAbuse of notation.  aAccuracy and precision.  aAdditive white Gaussian noise.  aAlgorithm.  aApproximation.  aAsymptotic analysis.  aBisection method.  aBoundary value problem.  aCalculation.  aCatastrophic failure.  aCombination.  aComputation.  aCondition number.  aContinuous function.  aControl theory.  aControl variable.  aDecision theory.  aDerivative.  aDetection.  aDeterministic system.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDifferential equation.  aDiscrete time and continuous time.  aDiscretization.  aDynamic programming.  aEngineering design process.  aEngineering.  aEquation.  aError message.  aEstimation theory.  aEstimation.  aFinite difference.  aGain scheduling.  aInequality (mathematics).  aInitial condition.  aIntegrator.  aInvertible matrix.  aLaplace transform.  aLeast squares.  aLikelihood function.  